Seagrasses are the only higher plants exclusively living in marine habitats (
). Currently, seagrasses are assigned to four different families Cymodoceaceae , Hydrocharitaceae , Posidoniaceae , and Zosteraceae (
;
). According to the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group III System, all four families belong to the monocot order
Alimatales ( Bremer et al., 2009 )
; while
preferred to treat the same clade as a subclass, Alismatidae. This results in the families of seagrasses to be divided into two different orders: Alismatales , containing seagrasses in the Hydrocharitaceae family and Potamogetonales , containing seagrasses in the Cymodoceaceae , Posidoniaceae , and Zosteraceae families (
). Cymodoceaceae are exclusively marine organisms and encompass a total of about fifteen species in five genera,
Amphibolis
,
Cymodocea
,
Halodule
,
Syringodium
, and
Thalassodendron
(
;
;
). Recently, the genus
Ruppia
which mainly inhabits brackish waters was also transferred to the Cymodoceaceae family (
). Though species of
Ruppia
are not regarded to be seagrasses in the strict sense by most authors, they are also covered here because of their phylogenetic position (
) and because of their ecological vicinity to ‘‘real” seagrasses.
Ruppia
primarily inhabits brackish waters and one not yet formally described species of
Ruppia
is regarded to be a real seagrass, i.e. exclusively living in fully marine habitats (
).

Seagrasses are of utmost importance for marine ecological systems close to the shore line. Many studies deal with the function of seagrasses as primary producers, shelter and food for fish, turtles, and invertebrates as well as spawning areas for these organisms and as habitats for epiphytes (

; 

; 

).

Existing reviews on seagrasses with a different focus than the present one deal in more detail with other aspects of the ecological role of these organisms and or particular compound classes, such as marine tannins (

), plant–herbivore interactions (

), functions of bioactive natural products from marine angiosperms (

), and plant-herbivore interactions, allelopathic properties, and anti-pathogen and anti-fouling activities of seagrasses (

). Readers primarily interested in these aspects of seagrasses are therefore referred to these publications as the aspects covered in detail in those reviews, though partially linked to seagrass secondary metabolites, are here only briessy mentioned.

Primary metabolites were only cursory covered in this review (in this section) and macromolecular compounds such as cell wall polysaccharides (

) and pectic galacturonans (

) were not covered. Seagrasses share their primary metabolism with higher plants inhabiting land and fresh water habitats, in particular with their closest relatives from the order 
Alismatales
s.l. (

).

Seagrasses like other photosynthetic higher plants have a lower light limit below which photosynthesis rates do not exceed respiration rates and therefore photosynthesis based plant life is not possible anymore. Under optimal water conditions (optimal water transparency and sufficiently high water temperatures), this point is reached between 50 and 
60 m
water depths in Europe (

) and 
90 m
water depths in the tropics (

). Indeed under optimal conditions, seagrass ecosystems range among the most productive ecosystems with regards to net primary production rates (

).

